Encapsidation, transmission and virion retention of wild type (WT) and minor coat protein (CPm) mutants of LIYV. (Left panel) Genetic map of the WT full-length LIYV CPm (WT; amino acid position [aa] 1–452), mutants with truncated CPms, 1-5b (aa 1–211) and R6M6 (aa 1–71), and the 1-5b mutant engineered with a restored full-length CPm (1-5bM1). The putative domains corresponding to aa 1–71 (domain I) and aa 72–452 (domain II) are indicated by the double-ended arrows. The numerical scale above the genetic maps indicates the relative sizes of the CPms. (Right panel) Immunogold-labeling TEM (IGL-TEM), transmission and virion retention analyses. IGL-TEM analyses: the filamentous virions/virion-like particles of WT, 1-5b, 1-5bM1 and R6M6 were tested by using antibodies produced against the LIYV CPm, followed by anti-rabbit IgG labeled with 5-nm gold particles. Micrographs of 1-5b and 1-5bM1 are reproduced from Stewart et al. [35] and Chen et al. [20••
