ce:section.ce:para:
NCSP viruses are transmitted by different but distinct insect vectors (Table 1
                     ). Transmission begins with virus acquisition. Optimal virus acquisition depends on whether or not virions are well positioned to capitalize on a vector's feeding behaviors (which encompass all known activities, including sampling and phloem-seeking/phloem-feeding, identifiable by patterns of voltage fluctuation, known as electrical penetration graph [EPG] waveforms, generated during insect–plant contacts [7]). Microscopic examinations of the tracks created by stylet-insertion in plants, in correlation with EPG waveforms, have revealed nuances in the feeding behaviors of different hemipterans [8,9]. Aphids navigate their stylets in between cells located along the pathway en route to the phloem sieve elements and tend to issue frequent bouts of sampling probes into these cells, including epidermal cells, early in the process [9,10] (Figure 1
                     a). In the case of whiteflies, although the stylet pathway to the phloem is also intercellular, they tend to engage in intracellular probes only much later, when their stylet bundles have reached deep into the plant tissue [11] (Figure 1a). Mealybugs also maneuver their stylets intercellularly, although they tend to make fewer (but longer) intracellular probes than aphids [12,13]. Leafhoppers are less nimble in intercellular stylet movement; because their stylets are much stouter, they tend to penetrate plant tissues in a direct route to the phloem, destroying cells along the way [14,15]. These disparate feeding behaviors in effect have intriguing biological implications for virus transmission. For example, because many viruses with an NCNP mode of transmission generally invade all plant cell types (i.e. they are tissue generalists), they stand a good chance of being acquired by aphids during early intracellular probing [16•
                     ]. By contrast, phloem tropism is more common among NCSP viruses; as such, virion acquisition is favored during phloem-feeding, and this is well represented by a number of whitefly-transmitted, leafhopper-transmitted and mealybug-transmitted viruses (Table 1). However, exceptions do exist, as exemplified by the aphid-transmitted Cauliflower mosaic virus (CaMV) and the whitefly-transmitted viruses in the genera Ipomovirus and Torradovirus, and Cowpea mild mottle virus, none of which are phloem-restricted (Table 1).

Studies of Lettuce infectious yellows virus (LIYV; genus Crinivirus) have shown that virions are retained in the foregut of its specific whitefly vector (Bemisia tabaci New World [NW] species; formerly B. tabaci biotype A) (Figure 1b and Table 1) and that the retained virions function in virus transmission. This was demonstrated by transmission assays conducted in parallel with membrane feeding and immunofluorescent localization (a typical example of the visualization of virion retention is presented in Figure 1b). The presence of specific signals in the foreguts of a significant number of virion-fed vectors corresponded with LIYV transmission. In contrast, insignificantly few diet-fed vectors harbored signals in their foreguts, and no corresponding LIYV transmission was observed. The number of virion-fed or diet-fed non-vectors (B. tabaci Middle East-Asia Minor 1 [MEAM 1] species; formerly B. tabaci biotype B) that harbored signals in their foreguts was also insignificant, and, collectively, none of them transmitted the virus [20••,33]. Using similar approaches, the specific retention and transmission of the crinivirus Lettuce chlorosis virus (LCV) by its whitefly vectors (both the B. tabaci MEAM 1 and NW species) have also been demonstrated recently (Chen and Ng, unpublished data). LIYV transmission is mediated by the proverbial ‘capsid strategy’ (Table 1), wherein transmission determinants are present on the virion capsid and no helper proteins are involved [5]. The LIYV virion is composed of four capsid components [34]. Of these, the minor coat protein (CPm) plays a pivotal role in mediating virion retention to the vector's foregut and this was determined using a combination of biochemical and molecular approaches and by transmission assays [20••
                        ]. The CPm determinants of LIYV transmission are unknown. However, there is information implicating the involvement of the CPm C-terminus in transmission, and that of the N terminal (approx. 71 amino acids) portion in interactions required for virion encapsidation (Tom Smith, personal communication). First, a natural mutant of LIYV (1-5b), with a 211-amino acid long CPm (the result of a >50% truncation of the wild type [WT] C-terminus), is defective in transmission and foregut retention (compared to the WT) [20••
                        ], and the truncated CPm does not appear to be incorporated in the virion (Figure 2
                        ) [35]. Second, a mutant (R6M6) engineered to produce an even shorter CPm (containing 71 amino acids from the WT N-terminus) is also transmission defective, but the truncated CPm appears to be incorporated in the virion (Figure 2). Thus, the first 71 residues may represent a domain that is essential for the interactions possibly needed for encapsidation. The fact that this truncated protein is insufficient for vector transmission suggests that the vector recognition domain probably lies toward the carboxyl terminus. Because the 1-5b CPm is not incorporated into the virion, this suggests that additional residues beyond the first 71 are not necessary for assembly but may in fact have a deleterious effect on protein folding. Ultimately, a high-resolution structure of the CPm will help identify the domains or amino acids involved in virion retention and transmission.
